\f0\b\fs28 Overview\

\f1\b0\fs24 This document is the formal, pre-registered trading plan for the MaxPain system. Its purpose is to consolidate in one place the structures, signals, entry and exit rules, and position-sizing discipline that have survived backtest validation, so that day-to-day trading decisions can be made against a written standard rather than in the moment. It is deliberately conservative: rules are committed here \i before\i0  they are used on live capital, and the paper-test window through approximately 2026-08-19 is binding regardless of how compelling any result looks in isolation. The plan is living \'97 findings that earn their keep get promoted in, findings that fail get moved to the caveats section, and every change is recorded in the revision log so the reasoning behind the current book is always auditable.\
\
The name MaxPain comes from the max-pain options theory: for any monthly expiration, the "max pain" strike is the one at which the largest dollar sum of in-the-money option value resides across calls and puts combined. The original hypothesis behind this system is that dealer delta-hedging against concentrated open interest near that strike creates a gravitational force that pulls the underlying toward max pain at expiration. Thirteen years of ORATS history tested at T-5 entry show this gravity is NOT causally present on average \'97 the underlying does not move toward max pain more than secular drift predicts. What remains tradeable is a distributional coincidence: certain names close within a narrow band of max pain far more often than others, and that signature is usable as a strike-selection anchor in specific structures (most notably the signal-filtered bull_put_mp variant).\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Universe: 150 Candidate Symbols\

\f1\b0\fs24 The trading plan operates on a pre-registered, frozen universe of 150 symbols. The list was selected on 2026-04-23 and committed to data/profile/universe_v1.parquet. The list is not modified during the paper-test window; changes require explicit versioning (v1.1, v2).\
\
\b Why pre-register the universe\b0\
\
\'95  Every backtest result is contingent on the universe it was run against\
\'95  Filtering names post-hoc to keep the ones that performed best measures hindsight, not edge\
\'95  Freezing the list before running any strategy cell disciplines the evidence\
\
\b Why 150, not more or fewer\b0\
\
\'95  Below 100: thin coverage when double-stratified (e.g., sector x vol regime) \'97 fewer than 10 names per cell\
\'95  Above 300: test noise grows faster than signal; dilutes the high-conviction archetype clusters\
\'95  150 is the smallest universe that survives double-stratification with at least 10 names per cell while keeping per-symbol N at roughly 170 cycles over 13 years of history\
\
\b Selection gates (all must pass)\b0\
\
\'95  Options liquidity: average daily volume > 1,000 contracts; front-month OI > 10,000; ATM bid-ask at most 10% of mid\
\'95  Stock liquidity: average daily dollar volume > $50M\
\'95  Listed at least 4 years before the backtest start date (protects survivorship integrity)\
\'95  Weekly expirations available\
\
\b Why archetype, not sector, drives allocation\b0\
\
Sector is a weak predictor of options behavior. AAPL and TSLA are both Technology and behave nothing alike. The final 150 was assembled by first clustering 3,992 history-eligible tickers on 11 behavioral features (aggregate OI and volume, contract count, weekly-expiration fraction, spot, ATM IV, IV regime range, skew, realized vol, VRP), then sampling within clusters under sector and cap constraints. Behavior groups names by how they actually trade \'97 which is what determines which structure wins on them.\
\
\b Final allocation (k=8 clustering)\b0\
\
\'95  \b Cluster 2 \'97 blue-chip premium-selling tier (60 names):\b0  SPY, QQQ, IWM, AAPL, MSFT, META, AMD, GLD, SLV, XLF, HYG and similar. High OI, deep weekly chains, moderate IV, modest VRP. Natural home of the bull_put book.\
\'95  \b Cluster 1 \'97 workhorse mid-to-large caps (50 names):\b0  TSM, RIO, TJX, NEE, DUK, DHR, TMO, CARR, SPG and similar.\
\'95  \b Cluster 0 \'97 troubled cyclicals and foreign ADRs (25 names):\b0  STLA, ITUB, SAN, CS, AR and similar. Higher IV, higher realized vol.\
\'95  \b Cluster 4 \'97 vol-toys and busted-IPO / meme candidates (15 names):\b0  VIX, VXX, NIO, RIVN, LCID, HOOD, SNAP, TLRY and similar. Reserved for long-vol structure testing, not for premium selling.\
\
\b Clusters deliberately excluded\b0\
\
\'95  Cluster 3 (niche / sparse-chain ETFs) \'97 positive VRP but mostly illiquid\
\'95  Cluster 5 (bankruptcies / near-bankruptcies), Cluster 6 (penny / micro-cap speculative), Cluster 7 (3-name reverse-skew anomaly, suspected data quirk) \'97 untradeable\
\
\b Explicit exclusions within the 150\b0\
\
\'95  Biotech names with binary FDA catalysts\
\'95  Perpetual M&A targets (spread pricing distorted by deal-spread dynamics)\
\'95  Names with multiple earnings-whipsaw cycles in the backtest window\
\
\b Known metadata caveats\b0\
\
\'95  A small number of tickers (BBT, ABX, K, STI, FCAU, CS, TWTR, YHOO, X, JCP, CTL) have been reassigned or delisted during the 13-year window. The ORATS historical data correctly reflects the historical owner during the trading window; only the current sector/cap label is stale.\
\'95  Mid-cap bucket is under-represented (~15 names versus a target of ~60). Top-OI ranking biases toward mega/large. Re-weighted allocation is v2 scope.\
\
\b How the universe flows into this plan\b0\
\
Each structure in this document names its own cohort from inside the 150. A name not on the universe list does not appear in the plan. New candidates become universe v1.1 with a dated log entry, and any backtest results on the extended set are reported separately from the v1 baseline.\
\
\b Cohort source of truth\b0\
\
Each structure deploys against a named code constant rather than against an embedded list. The authoritative cohort lives in scripts/qualifier/gate_config.py:\
\
\'95  COHORT_BULL_PUT \'97 bull put 30\uc0\u916  on Window A and Window B\
\'95  COHORT_BEAR_CALL \'97 bear call 30\uc0\u916  on Window A (regime-gated)\
\'95  COHORT_INVERTED_FLY_PAIR \'97 inverted fly run alongside bull_put on the same name\
\'95  COHORT_INVERTED_FLY_SINGLE \'97 inverted fly standalone (no pair partner)\
\'95  COHORT_ZEBRA_TIER1 / COHORT_ZEBRA_TIER2 \'97 synthetic-stock tiers (Tier 1 high-conviction Mag-7 + indices, Tier 2 broad diversifiers)\
\'95  COHORT_EARNINGS_BULL_PUT / _BEAR_CALL / _INVERTED_FLY \'97 earnings-track cohorts\
\'95  COHORT_COVERED_CALL \'97 covered call on credit ETFs\
\
The plan describes the SELECTION CRITERIA that put a name into a cohort and the BACKTEST EVIDENCE that supported the inclusion at the time of writing. Cohort membership itself is expected to rotate as new universes are tested, names are excluded by walk-forward, and findings refresh. \b Cohort changes do not require plan revisions \'97 they require gate_config.py edits and corresponding memory entries\b0 . The plan revision log notes only architectural changes, methodology updates, or strategies promoted / demoted as a whole.\
\
Names that have been TESTED and EXCLUDED with a documented reason stay in this plan because the reason generalizes (e.g., "TLT excluded from covered call because long-duration Treasury ETF lacks the floating-rate par-anchor mechanics"). The plan-level lesson is the value, not the membership status.\
\
Per-name backtest evidence (per-cycle mean, win rate, capture ratio, walk-forward train/val behavior) appearing throughout this document is historical record from the test that established the cohort at the time the section was written. These numbers do not auto-refresh. If the cohort rotates and you want updated evidence, re-run the relevant backtest script and update the memory entry; the plan can stay as-is until a structure-level promotion / demotion warrants a revision.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 The Pinner Cohort\

\f1\b0\fs24 Within the 150-symbol universe, the subset of names that actually pin reliably near max pain is smaller. The MP-anchored structures in this plan (most notably bull_put_mp and the forward-test bear_call_mp variants) only apply to this subset; generic 30-delta verticals and the Window A bull_put apply to the broader universe.\
\
\b How pinning was measured\b0\
\
\'95  Primary metric: median |close - MP| / close across all 13 years of monthly OpEx cycles (continuous, scale-free)\
\'95  Secondary metric: fraction of cycles where close lands within 1% of max pain (binary)\
\'95  Max pain computed at T-1 (Thursday EOD before OpEx Friday) from that day's chain open interest\
\'95  Scan covered 19,400 cycles across all 150 tickers \'97 script at scripts/backtest/pin_reliability_scan.py, results at data/profile/pin_reliability_per_cycle.parquet\
\
\b Four-tier cohort that emerged\b0\
\
\'95  \b Tier 1 \'97 credit and bond ETFs (4 names):\b0  BKLN, HYG, JNK, TLT. Median 1.0-1.5% off MP, 37-52% of cycles within 1%. The tightest pinners in the universe.\
\'95  \b Tier 2 \'97 major equity indices (5 names):\b0  SPX, SPY, DIA, QQQ, IWM. Median 1.6-2.4% off MP, 21-31% within 1%.\
\'95  \b Tier 3 \'97 sector ETFs and dividend stalwarts (10 names):\b0  XLU, XLV, IYR, VNQ, EFA, GLD, VZ, KO, PG, WMT. Median 2.0-2.6% off MP, 23-28% within 1%.\
\'95  \b Tier 4 \'97 excluded from MP-anchored strategies:\b0  vol-toys and momentum names (LCID, ENPH, TIGR, CAR, RIG, HOOD, TLRY, VXX, MU, MP, SBSW). Median 9-20% off MP \'97 the mechanic has no meaningful gravity on them. Note: "MP" here is the ticker (Mountain Pass), not the max-pain abbreviation used elsewhere in this document.\
\
\b Non-obvious finding\b0\
\
The tightest pinners are credit/bond ETFs, not the equity indices most often associated with max pain in popular discussion. BKLN pinning within 1% of MP more than half the time is a remarkably strong distributional effect \'97 but Phase 2 testing showed the tightest pinners are also the \i least\i0  exploitable because their options are too thin to trade at the strikes required.\
\
\b Caveat\b0\
\
The statistical pin is real; a \i causal\i0  gravitational effect was not demonstrated at T-5 entry (see Overview). Pinner-cohort status is a useful universe-characterization flag, not a standalone trading signal.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Primary Trading Windows\

\f1\b0\fs24 This plan operates in two non-overlapping trading windows. Trades outside these windows are not part of the plan.\
\
\b Window A \'97 45-DTE Managed.\b0  Enter at ~45 days to expiration. Exit on first trigger of either 21 DTE or 50% of max profit. Purpose: harvest the core of the theta curve at realistic delta and wing widths, with management rules that cap both sides of the tail. Candidate structures: bull_put and bear_call verticals, iron condor, short strangle, and inverted_fly (long-vol hedge, opposite regime). Rolling is permitted under defined triggers \'97 see Management.\
\
\b Window B \'97 Near-OpEx Theta Harvest.\b0  Enter 5 trading days before OpEx Friday (T-5). Exit timing is structure-specific: the only validated spec in this plan is bull_put_mp held to expiration. Purpose: collect the final theta acceleration on OpEx-anchored option combinations. Candidate structures: ATM or near-ATM iron flies, iron condors, short strangles, and MP-anchored verticals where entry signals permit \'97 each with its own exit spec in its section. \i Caveat:\i0  a T-3 exit rule was tested and hurts 7 of 8 premium-seller structures, because the theta payoff concentrates in the final 2 trading days. Do not apply a blanket D-3 exit. Forward-test results on individual Window B structures are the binding evidence; iron fly, iron condor, and strangle Window B specs are pending.\
\
\b Why two windows, not one.\b0  The 45-DTE and near-OpEx trades are structurally different P&L mechanics even when they share an underlying or a structure. Paper-track results are reported per window so a win or loss in one window does not contaminate inference about the other.\
\
\b Paper-test window.\b0  Both windows operate under paper-only discipline through approximately 2026-08-19. No live capital is committed in either window before that date, regardless of backtest or paper-track results.\
\
\b Paper-test falsification and promotion criteria.\b0  A paper-test window is only meaningful if it can fail the plan. The binding review questions at the 2026-08-19 gate:\
\
\'95  \b Bull_put.\b0  Did the shortlist accumulate at least 10 closed monthly OpEx cycles? If fewer, extend paper-test; do not promote on thin evidence. If 10+, is aggregate mean P&L per cycle above zero at the friction actually incurred (not the backtest friction)? Below zero on 10+ cycles is a falsification and forces a rewrite of the bull_put section, not an extension.\
\'95  \b Bear_call.\b0  Did the H1 filter (SPY < 200dma AND SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5) fire and produce at least 1 closed cycle? If it never fired during the paper window, bear_call remains backtest-only \'97 do not promote to live on zero live evidence, regardless of how much time passed. If it fired 5+ times, is mean P&L per cycle positive? If yes, candidate for live at reduced size. If no, bear_call H1 rewrite required.\
\'95  \b Rolling rule (bull_put_mp T2_mtm down-and-out).\b0  Did the roll trigger fire at least 3 times? On those triggered cycles, did the rolled combined P&L beat the accept-loss baseline of roughly \'96$0.26? Below baseline is a falsification.\
\'95  \b Live-capital breach.\b0  Did any live capital enter via either window during the paper-test period? If yes, audit what slipped through and tighten the discipline before proceeding.\
\
Rolling the paper-test forward without rewriting the plan is a recognized failure mode \'97 if the evidence is pointing at a falsification, the correct move is to rewrite the relevant section, not to buy more time.\
\

