\f0\b\fs28 Position Sizing\

\f1\b0\fs24 \i Scope: sizing rules for bull_put, bear_call, inverted_fly, ZEBRA, and covered call. Inverted fly sizing is described in its own section (by dollar debit per contract). ZEBRA and covered call sizing are described below \'97 both capital-outlay-based, not per-contract \'97 because per-contract debits / stock costs range from ~$2K (BKLN covered call) to ~$70K (AMZN ZEBRA). Iron condors and iron flies were tested and rejected.\i0\
\
\b First-pass caveat.\b0  The specific percentages below (1.5% per bull_put position, 0.5% per bear_call, 3% per underlying, 40% per cluster, SPX 3x weighting, 15% book-wide) are first-pass defaults for a new trading system. They are not derived from a tested sizing study \'97 they are conservative judgment calls anchored to the defined-risk max losses already present in the strategy. Only paper-test and live experience through the 2026-08-19 window and beyond will tell whether these caps are too tight, too loose, or correctly calibrated. Treat them as a starting discipline, revisit at cycle closes, and update this section in the Revision Log as experience accumulates.\
\
\b Core thesis\b0\
\
Size by dollar risk (notional max loss), not by contract count. One SPX contract is roughly 100x one XLU contract in dollar terms; contract-based sizing would concentrate risk in a single name.\
\
\b Per-position dollar risk caps\b0\
\
\'95  Each bull_put position: max loss <= 1.5% of account capital\
\'95  Each bear_call position (when deployed): max loss <= 0.5% of account capital (one-third bull_put sizing per Regime Overrides)\
\'95  On a $100,000 base: approximately $1,500 max risk per bull_put, $500 max risk per bear_call\
\
\b Concentration caps\b0\
\
\'95  \b Per underlying:\b0  total max loss across all positions on the same symbol <= 3% of account\
\'95  \b Per cluster:\b0  total max loss in any single archetype cluster <= 40% of total book max loss\
\'95  \b Per GICS sector:\b0  no more than 2 single-name positions in the same GICS sector per OpEx cycle (SHIPPED 2026-05-15). ETFs (broad-market or sector) are exempt \'97 they are already aggregate exposure. Enforced mechanically in the cycle qualifier: if more than 2 candidates qualify in the same sector for the same OpEx, rank by verdict tier (GO > DOWNSIZE) with alphabetical tiebreaker and keep the top 2; lower-ranked candidates receive a SKIP_CONCENTRATION verdict. Daily alert surfaces a \uc0\u8226  SECTOR-LOAD warning on the second entry per sector, even before the cap fires, so the second entry is a conscious decision rather than silent stacking. Triggered by the 2026-05-12 WFC + JPM same-cohort stop pattern: a correlation cluster is not two independent risk events. Detail memory: project_sector_concentration_cap.md.\
\'95  \b SPX-specific:\b0  SPX max loss counts triple against the per-cluster cap \'97 a $3,000 SPX position consumes the same concentration budget as a $9,000 position in another cluster-2 name\
\'95  \b Book-wide:\b0  total max loss across all open bull_put + bear_call positions <= 15% of account capital at any time\
\
\b Bull_put vs bear_call sizing ratio\b0\
\
\'95  Normal bull regime: bull_put at full size; bear_call at zero\
\'95  Confirmed bear meeting the 4-condition deployment gate: bull_put downsizes per Regime Overrides soft triggers; bear_call deploys at one-third the comparable bull_put dollar-risk cap\
\'95  Total book max-loss budget does not change between regimes; composition does\
\
\b Soft-downsize triggers (from Regime Overrides)\b0\
\
When any soft-downsize trigger fires (SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.7, SPY near 200dma from above trending down, term inverted + VIX > 20): cut new bull_put entries to 50% of the cap until the triggers resolve.\
\
\b ZEBRA sizing \'97 capital-outlay-based, NOT per-contract\b0\
\
ZEBRA does not fit the dollar-risk-cap framework above because its sizing constraint is the upfront debit (capital tied up), not max loss as a percentage of account. A single AMZN ZEBRA contract carries $40K\'96$70K of capital outlay; an SPY contract is ~$7K. Per-contract sizing would either over-deploy capital on high-priced names or under-deploy on indices.\
\
\'95  \b Capital outlay per ZEBRA position:\b0  5\'9610% of book equity. For a $100K paper-test book, target $5K\'96$10K outlay per ZEBRA, then divide by per-contract debit to get the contract count (rounded down).\
\'95  \b Tier 1 names\b0  (high-conviction Mag-7 + indices, see COHORT_ZEBRA_TIER1): size at the upper end of the range (8\'9610%).\
\'95  \b Tier 2 names\b0  (broad diversifiers, see COHORT_ZEBRA_TIER2): size at the lower end (5\'967%).\
\'95  \b Capital-outlay caps in practice:\b0  high-priced single names with per-contract debits above $20K (Mag-7 names trade in this range) yield 0\'961 contracts on a $100K book under the 10% cap. Either commit one full contract (consuming 50%+ of the ZEBRA budget) or skip the name. Index ETFs and lower-priced cohort members fit cleanly. AMZN at $40K\'96$70K debit per contract is effectively excluded under any retail book under $700K.\
\'95  \b Total ZEBRA book-equity allocation:\b0  no more than 30% of book equity in open ZEBRA positions at one time. Combined with the 15% book-wide max-loss cap on credit spreads, this leaves ~55% of book in cash or money market \'97 acceptable for paper testing.\
\'95  \b Worst-case loss:\b0  capped at debit per contract. The full debit is realized only if spot expires at or below the long-call strike. Sizing must contemplate a 100% loss of the upfront debit on a given position \'97 do not anchor on the historical mean P&L when sizing.\
\
\b Paper-test window\b0\
\
All sizing rules above apply to paper capital through approximately 2026-08-19. Live capital deployment requires explicit reconsideration beyond that date.\
\
\b When the book is at cap\b0\
\
\'95  Do not add new positions even if a high-conviction signal fires. Wait for an exit or roll to free budget.\
\'95  Do not oversize to chase an attractive setup. The discipline is the edge.\
\
\b Loss-cap discipline (2x rule)\b0\
\
A position's max realized loss must not exceed 2x its target win. This is a structural quality gate at trade selection time, not a stop-loss rule. For credit verticals, target win = entry credit and max loss = wing \'97 credit, so the rule reduces to credit / wing \uc0\u8805 0.333 (max loss \uc0\u8804 2x credit means wing \uc0\u8804 3x credit).\
\
The rule excludes structurally bad trades \'97 trades where you risk $4 to make $1, where one loss eats four wins. The 2x cap matches the empirical loss/win ratio implied by managed-exit win rates around 70-80%: a 75% cohort with 1:1 risk/reward breaks even, while 2:1 requires a 67% win rate to break even, which the validated cohorts clear by 5-15 points.\
\
spread_score_tracker.py MIN_CREDIT_WIDTH was raised from 0.35 to 0.50 on 2026-04-28 to enforce credit/wing \uc0\u8805 0.50 at scan time. New entries below this threshold do not earn GO verdicts. Existing trades that violate the rule are not retroactively closed.\
\
ZEBRA does not reduce to credit/wing math (debit structure, no fixed wing). MTM-stop discipline for ZEBRA is the next layer; not yet specified.\
\
\b Expensive names \'97 verticals only\b0\
\
Stocks priced above approximately $100 spot get credit verticals only; ZEBRA, inverted fly, and Jade Lizard structures are reserved for sub-$100 names. Personal-trading budget rule established 2026-04-28, not a backtest finding.\
\
ZEBRA on a $200 spot is a $14K-$20K capital outlay per contract; an inverted fly at 10% wings on a $200 spot is a $2K-$3K debit per contract; both are uneconomic on a paper-test or small live book. Verticals scale linearly with strike width regardless of spot, so a $5-wide bull_put on a $200 stock is the same ~$500 max loss as a $5-wide bull_put on a $50 stock.\
\
Exception: index ETFs (SPY, QQQ, DIA, IWM) and SPX trade above $100 but are explicitly retained for ZEBRA Tier 1 and IF pair-book duty \'97 index-level capital outlay is acceptable per the ZEBRA capital-outlay framework. The rule applies to high-priced single-name equities specifically: NVDA / GOOGL / META at $200+ are excluded from IF and Jade Lizard but remain in ZEBRA Tier 1 because the structure is purpose-built for high-priced underlyings.\
\
\b Covered call sizing \'97 capital-outlay-based, NOT per-contract\b0\
\
Like ZEBRA, the constraint is upfront capital tied up rather than max-loss percentage. Per-contract capital is the full stock cost: BKLN ~$2,200, JNK ~$7,500, HYG ~$8,300.\
\
\'95  Capital outlay per covered call position: 5\'9610% of book equity. For a $100K paper-test book, target $5K\'9610K outlay per position, then divide by spot price to get the share count (round to lots of 100).\
\'95  Total covered-call book-equity allocation: \uc0\u8804  20% of book equity in open covered_call positions at one time. Combined with the 30% ZEBRA cap and the 15% bull_put + bear_call cap, this leaves \uc0\u8776  35% of book in cash or money market \'97 acceptable for paper testing.\
\'95  Worst-case loss is bounded by structural-anchor mechanics, not by a hard floor. The worst tested cycle in 13 years was \'96$4.43/share on BKLN (March 2020 COVID), which fully recovered within 2 weeks. Sizing should contemplate a 20% temporary drawdown on a given position during a credit-cycle dislocation, even though long-run mean is strongly positive.\
\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Regime Overrides\

\f1\b0\fs24 Bull put and bear call are not two strategies with independent edges. They are the same edge running in opposite directions, and the edge lives in regime selection. This section captures what we know about regime identification and how to adjust sizing when the regime is unclear.\
\
\b The core asymmetry (backtested, 2013-2026)\b0\
\
Managed-exit, dte_45 entry, slip=0.25, full 150 universe. Mean P&L per cycle:\
\
\'95  Non-crash: bull_put +$0.040, bear_call -$0.099\
\'95  COVID 2020: bull_put -$0.531, bear_call +$0.107\
\'95  2022 bear: bull_put -$0.150, bear_call +$0.098\
\'95  Dec 2018: bull_put -$0.574, bear_call +$0.177\
\'95  Aug 2015: bull_put -$0.185, bear_call +$0.136\
\'95  Volmageddon 2018: bull_put -$0.279, bear_call +$0.212\
\
The sign flips cleanly in every tested bear window. The 14-year sample is bull-dominated, which is why bull_put carries the baseline edge \'97 that is a regime fact, not a structural advantage.\
\
\b Which signals predict the flip? (Signal study, 2026-04-24)\b0\
\
Tested individual signals against forward 45-day drawdowns <= -7% across 13 years of SPY data. Base rate = 15.5% of days are followed by a -7% drawdown within 45 days.\
\
\i Individual signal precision (crash rate when signal fires):\i0\
\
\'95  SPY < 200-day MA: 33.2%, 2.15x lift \'97 strongest, but reactive (fires after drawdown has begun)\
\'95  IV rank 252-day > 0.7: 29.0%, 1.88x \'97 best predictive signal; fires 5.5% of days\
\'95  Term structure inverted (front > back): 22.3%, 1.44x\
\'95  ATM IV > 0.2: 20.5%, 1.33x\
\'95  \b SPY > +10% over 200-day MA: 9.7%, 0.63x \'97 DIS-informative.\b0  Overbought markets are statistically safer than average, not more dangerous.\
\'95  SPY > +15% over 200-day MA: 1.9%, 0.12x \'97 strongly counter-intuitive.\
\
\i Composite-signal precision:\i0\
\
\'95  At least 2 of 5 conditions firing: 17.0%, 1.10x \'97 essentially noise\
\'95  At least 3 of 5 firing: 24.3%, 1.58x \'97 modest lift, fires 5% of days\
\
\i Per-downturn composite firing at T-20:\i0  COVID fires (2/5), 2022 bear fires (3/5), Dec 2018 does not fire, Aug 2015 does not fire, Volmageddon does not fire. \b Two of five tested downturns came with essentially no advance warning.\b0\
\
\b Weekly IV-HV and trend persistence (tested 2026-04-24)\b0\
\
Daily IV/HV crossovers are too noisy to act on. A weekly aggregation was tested directly, with 5-week forward trend persistence (same side of 50-day MA) as the outcome.\
\
\i Baseline: 5-week trend persistence = 64.2% of weeks\i0\
\
\i The trend-is-your-friend axiom is asymmetric:\i0\
\
\'95  \b In a bull (SPY > 50dma):\b0  trend holds 5 weeks 75.2% of the time; average forward 5-week return +0.80%\
\'95  \b In a bear (SPY < 50dma):\b0  trend holds 5 weeks only 34.6% of the time; average forward 5-week return \b +2.03%\b0\
\
When SPY is below its 50-day MA, the base rate is a rally back within 25 days, not continuation of weakness. This is the Dec 2018 V-bottom pattern and the Aug 2015 flash-crash-then-recovery pattern. Bears mean-revert faster than bulls do.\
\
\i Weekly VRP sign stability as a modest confirmation signal:\i0\
\
\'95  Bull + VRP same sign >= 8 weeks: 80.2% 5-week persistence (small lift over 75.2% bull baseline)\
\'95  Bear + VRP same sign >= 8 weeks: 34.8% (no lift over 34.6% bear baseline)\
\
Weekly VRP stability adds small conviction in a bull, none in a bear.\
\
\i Boom-from-tranquility events:\i0  Dec 2018 and Volmageddon both occurred from 10+ weeks of stable positive VRP. No weekly signal gave any warning for these events. Sizing discipline and defined-risk structure are the only defense.\
\
\b Soft-downsize triggers (not hard stops)\b0\
\
When any of these fire, cut new bull_put entry size by 50% and do not add new positions beyond half size:\
\
\'95  SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.7\
\'95  SPY within 2% of its 200-day moving average from above, trending down\
\'95  Term structure inverted AND VIX > 20\
\
\b Hard pause trigger\b0\
\
When all three of these fire, stop opening new bull_put positions entirely until the set resolves:\
\
\'95  SPY below 200-day moving average\
\'95  Term structure inverted\
\'95  SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5\
\
\b Bear_call deployment gate (validated H1 filter, 2026-04-24)\b0\
\
Tested on 2,686 Phase 2h cycles. The validated filter is:\
\
\'95  \b SPY below 200-day moving average\b0\
\'95  \b SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5\b0\
\
Under this two-condition gate: mean +$0.092/cycle, 40% win rate, N=102 over 13 years of history. Lifts baseline by +$0.179.\
\
\b Important negative finding:\b0  term structure inversion does NOT improve the gate. Adding "term inverted" to the filter HURTS performance (the SPY<200dma + term-inverted cohort produces -$0.152/cycle). The intuition-driven hypothesis of "symmetric opposite of bull_put calm-regime filter" is falsified.\
\
\b Additional durability precaution (not directly tested, derived from trend-persistence asymmetry):\b0  because bear trends persist only 35% of 5-week windows, consider requiring SPY has been below its 50-day MA for at least 4 consecutive weeks before deploying \'97 evidence the bear has legs, not just onset. This is a conservative overlay, not a validated filter.\
\
\b Deliberate asymmetry between bull_put pause and bear_call deploy gates.\b0  The bull_put hard-pause trigger requires three conditions (SPY < 200dma AND term inverted AND SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5). The bear_call deployment gate requires only two (SPY < 200dma AND SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5) \'97 term inversion is deliberately NOT required. This is not an oversight. The H1 filter test showed term inversion is DIS-informative for bear_call entry (adding "term inverted" to the SPY<200dma+IVR>0.5 filter drops mean P&L from +$0.092 to \'96$0.152 per cycle). So in a "SPY < 200dma + SPY IVR > 0.5 + contango" regime, the bull_put book is at soft-downsize (half-size, not paused) while the bear_call gate fires and new bear_call positions can be opened. Both books can run simultaneously in that regime. Hard pause of bull_put waits for the additional term-inversion confirmation because bull_put, unlike bear_call, actually benefits from avoiding the full three-condition stress state. Read this asymmetry as evidence-supported, not as a logical inconsistency.\
\
\b Sizing:\b0  new bear_call positions at one-third of comparable bull_put dollar risk until at least 10 live/paper cycles validate. Expect H1 filter to fire on roughly 4% of trading days \'97 bear_call is an occasional trade, not a persistent book.\
\
\b Rolling:\b0  do NOT roll bear_call positions. Tested as H3 and falsified \'97 rolling compounds losses in persistent bulls. Hold to expiry per management rules.\
\
\b What we cannot do\b0\
\
\'95  Algorithmically switch from bull_put to bear_call based on any single signal or signal combination\
\'95  Pre-position bear_call ahead of a suspected downturn \'97 wrong-footedness on the 40% of crashes that come without warning will exceed the edge on the 60% that do\
\'95  Use an overbought condition as a risk signal \'97 the data says strong bull runs statistically predict continued calm\
\
\b What we accept\b0\
\
\'95  Some bear regimes will drop a bull_put-heavy book into a meaningful drawdown before any signal fires. This is a cost of participating in the bull_put edge. Sizing discipline (caps on total bull_put dollar risk, diversification across the 12-name shortlist) is the primary defense, not regime prediction.\
\'95  Dec 2018 and Volmageddon 2018 both occurred from 10+ weeks of stable positive VRP with SPY trending well above its 50dma. No signal in our tested set warned of either event. These "boom from tranquility" events are irreducible surprises; defined-risk structure is the only defense.\
\'95  Entering bear_call at a bear onset may give up real edge if the bear proves sustained (like 2022). This is a deliberate trade-off \'97 we prefer missing some bear-onset edge over being wrong-footed by the 65% of bear weeks that resolve with a rally.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Regime Transition\
\
\f1\b0\fs24 The Regime Overrides section above specifies what fires WHEN. This section specifies what to DO when triggers fire while you have an existing book. The plan operates on a paper-test 4+ month window with rolling positions across multiple structures \'97 a regime change is a process, not a switch, and the book has to manage itself through it.\
\
The 2026-04-25 H1 alignment audit on the SPY ORATS history (2013-2026, 11 discrete bear events) confirmed that H1 is high-precision and moderate-recall. 97.6% of all H1-firing days (across 13 years) fell INSIDE a real bear event. False positives totaled 7 days in the entire sample. Lead time relative to the trough averaged 25-50 trading days on fast bears (2018Q4, COVID, 2022 phases, 2025Q2) and was useless on slow grinds (2018Q1, 2023). The signal is reliable as a confirmation, weak as an early warning.\
\
\b Five-stage transition framework\b0\
\
\'95  \b Stage 1 \'97 Soft-downsize triggers fire (any of: SPY 252-day IVR > 0.7; SPY within 2% of 200dma trending down; term inverted AND VIX > 20).\b0  \i Action:\i0  cut new bull_put entries to 50% size; pause new ZEBRA entries; permit new IF entries on term-inversion days; bear_call still NOT permitted; existing positions run to their normal exits.\
\'95  \b Stage 2 \'97 SPY breaks below 200dma but IVR < 0.5.\b0  \i Action:\i0  bull_put hard pause if also term_inv + IVR>0.5; otherwise still 50% size; IF active on term-inversion days; bear_call still NOT permitted (waiting on IVR); ZEBRA held; earnings T1 continues per calendar.\
\'95  \b Stage 3 \'97 H1 fires (SPY < 200dma AND IVR > 0.5).\b0  \i Action:\i0  bear_call permitted on the COHORT_BEAR_CALL set (broad equity indices and one defensive-consumer name; see gate_config.py for current membership); bull_put new entries paused if hard-pause also active; IF continues; ZEBRA held; earnings T1 unchanged. \b Critical: do not deploy bear_call on any name where you have an open bull_put on the same monthly OpEx expiration.\b0  Bull_put + bear_call on the same name same expiration = an iron condor, which we tested and rejected.\
\'95  \b Stage 4 \'97 Decline plays out toward trough.\b0  \i Action:\i0  bull_put MTM-1x roll triggers on rollable names (SPX, SPY, QQQ, DIA, WMT, TLT, VNQ); names not on the roll list (XLU, IYR, XLV, KO) hold to expiry and absorb the loss per defined-risk sizing; bear_call positions opened at Stage 3 manage to their exits; IF positions likely hit 50%-profit-target; ZEBRA approaches max loss on names where spot falls below the long-call strike (~13-21% below entry on Tier 1).\
\'95  \b Stage 5 \'97 Recovery (H1 false-positive zone).\b0  \i Action:\i0  bear_call new entries STOP when SPY closes back above its 200dma. Do not rely on H1 turning off \'97 H1 fires on 19-75% of recovery days because price stays below 200dma well after IVR has compressed. Bull_put and ZEBRA remain in their soft-downsize cadence until BOTH conditions clear (SPY > 200dma AND IVR < 0.5). RSI-14 bullish divergence (validated +4.71% fwd 25-day return) is a candidate confirmation for resuming full-size bull_put deployment but is not yet promoted in the plan; treat as a soft "regime stabilizing" tell, not a deploy trigger.\
\
\b Per-name conflict rules\b0\
\
The cohort overlap between bull_put and bear_call covers four names (SPY, QQQ, DIA, WMT). When the regime rotates, these four names are where the "accidental iron condor" risk is highest.\
\
\'95  \b No bull_put + bear_call on the same name same monthly OpEx expiration.\b0  Wait for the bull_put to close (or roll) before adding bear_call. The bull_put MTM-1x trigger will close most positions naturally during a real bear; non-rollable names hold to expiry, after which the next monthly OpEx is open for bear_call deployment.\
\'95  \b ZEBRA + bear_call on the same name is undefined, prefer not to layer.\b0  ZEBRA delta is ~+1.0 per contract; adding a 30\uc0\u916  bear_call on the same name reduces net delta to ~+0.70 \'97 a partial trim, not a real hedge. If you want to neutralize ZEBRA delta in a regime change, the right tool is closing or rolling the ZEBRA, not stacking bear_call. Pay friction without buying real protection.\
\'95  \b ZEBRA + IF on the same name is the natural regime hedge.\b0  ZEBRA is long delta + long gamma; IF is long vega + long gamma (long-vol). In a crash, ZEBRA loses (capped at debit) and IF profits from vol expansion + magnitude. Net: IF leg covers a portion of ZEBRA loss. Not separately tested as a paired book in the v1.6 work, but the structures are aligned and both validated standalone. Treat as a deliberate pairing rule: if ZEBRA is open on a name, an IF entry on the same name + same expiration is encouraged when the IF gate (term inversion) fires.\
\'95  \b Earnings T1 cohort runs independent of the transition.\b0  The earnings cohorts (COHORT_EARNINGS_BULL_PUT plus the INTC bear_call and PLTR inverted_fly single-name carve-outs) operate per the per-name calendar; directional bias is name-specific not regime-driven. Continue per the plan even during Stages 1-5.\
\
\b Timing reality and what the plan accepts\b0\
\
\'95  In the 2018Q4-style fast bear: H1 fires P+5 to P+21 days after the peak, T-25 to T-50 days before the trough. Useful warning. Stages 1\'963 unfold in compressed time (often within a single OpEx cycle). Bear_call deployment lands in the productive window.\
\'95  In the COVID-style flash crash: H1 fires P+8 days but T-25 days. Bear_call deployment is reactive, not predictive \'97 you're capturing the ongoing-vol harvest, not the move itself. Sizing has to respect the possibility that you're entering near the trough.\
\'95  In the 2022-style secular bear: H1 fires multiple times across a 9-month decline (events 7, 8, 9 in the alignment audit). Repeated bear_call deployments. Bull_put rolls multiple times on rollable names. ZEBRA exposure ages out over the 75-DTE cycle and reopens at lower spot \'97 effectively averages into the bear floor.\
\'95  In a 2018Q1 / 2023-style slow grind: H1 fires only at the trough, on 2-3% of decline days. Bear_call is essentially absent. The plan accepts this loss of edge in slow grinds \'97 attempting to deploy bear_call without H1 confirmation has been tested (Phase 2h baseline) and loses money.\
\'95  In the recovery: H1 false-positives last 1-3 months past the trough. The Stage 5 SPY-above-200dma cutoff is the workaround \'97 simpler and more conservative than waiting for H1 to disengage.\
\
\b Daily regime-state tracking (operational)\b0\
\
The 9:20 ET research-cohort capture cron (research_cohort_snapshot.py) is extended in v1.7 to compute and persist the regime stage daily into a new regime_state table in metal_project.db. The cycle qualifier (build window 2026-05-01 to 2026-05-04) reads this state to populate the per-symbol GO/PAUSE/DOWNSIZE grid before each entry day. Operationally, the user does not need to recompute regime state at deployment time \'97 the daily state is available, dated, and auditable.\
\
\b What this section does NOT do\b0\
\
\'95  Force-close existing positions on any signal. Existing positions run to their structure-specific exit rules. Regime transition affects NEW entries and SIZING, not forced closures of in-flight cycles.\
\'95  Add a "panic mode" override. There is no rule in the plan for closing an entire book on a single signal. The structural sizing rules (max-loss caps, ZEBRA capital outlay caps) carry the tail-risk discipline; regime transition adjusts the entry mix without touching the existing book.\
\'95  Specify a hedging ratio. The IF + ZEBRA pairing is a directional pairing, not a delta-neutral hedge. The book remains net-directional; regime transition adjusts net direction over a 4-8 week period as old positions close and new positions of opposite tilt come on.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Decision Support Infrastructure\

\f1\b0\fs24 This section describes the operational tooling that supports day-to-day decisions against the rules above. The plan is the standard; the tools enforce the standard at qualifier time, post-mortem time, and daily-alert time.\
\
\b Cycle qualifier (daily 9:25 ET cron)\b0\
\
scripts/qualifier/cycle_qualifier.py runs each weekday morning, reads the current regime_state, computes per-symbol per-structure verdicts (GO, DOWNSIZE, PENDING, SKIP, PAUSE), and persists results to cycle_qualifier_runs in metal_project.db plus a dated parquet. Implements every gate in this plan: bull_put signal gate (contango + VRP > 0), bear_call H1 gate (SPY < 200dma + IVR > 0.5), IF term-inversion gate, ZEBRA 75-DTE entry, covered_call monthly entry (trading day after prior OpEx), earnings-track T-1 / T-3 calendar matching, soft-downsize and hard-pause triggers, and per-name overrides (GOOGL no-IF-gate, SCCO and CNQ T-1 earnings entry).\
\
\b Earnings-in-holding-window gate.\b0  The qualifier also enforces the plan rule "no binary earnings inside the DTE window" \'97 for every non-earnings-bias structure, if any earnings event for the symbol falls in [target, opex] inclusive, the verdict is downgraded to SKIP. Earnings-bias structures (the *_earnings cohorts) bypass the gate by design, since their holding window straddles the earnings event on purpose.\
\
\b Cycle post-mortem (run at OpEx close)\b0\
\
scripts/postmortem/cycle_postmortem_qualifier.py is the audit step run after a cycle closes. It produces six sections: VERDICT OUTCOMES (split actual book vs algo recs), COUNTERFACTUAL (GO verdicts not taken), PER-TRADE SIGNAL-STATE ATTRIBUTION (signal at entry x outcome), SIGNAL ACCURACY SCORECARD (forward-test of each signal vs pre-registered backtest expected lift, with VALIDATED / FALSIFIED / NULL verdicts), DIRECTIONAL OUTCOME vs PREDICTION (SPY realized return vs term-spread / 200dma claims), and REGIME SIGNAL FLIPS (cycle-window scoped). Backfills regime state from SPY ORATS for trades placed before regime_state DB capture began on 2026-04-25.\
\
\b Pre-registration discipline.\b0  The signal accuracy scorecard tags VALIDATED / FALSIFIED / NULL against pre-registered claims sealed in docs/SIGNAL_VALIDATION_PREREG.md (2026-04-26). The discipline is that retroactive rationalization cannot promote a NULL into a VALIDATED \'97 the pre-reg is the standard.\
\
\b Daily alert (4:45 PM ET cron)\b0\
\
scripts/monitor/daily_alert.py runs at 4:45 PM ET each weekday and emits a focused multi-section summary of the day's actionable items. Replaced the prior gamma-noise alert (Metal_Project) with empirical p95 thresholds per ticker and fresh-breach-only logic. Sections, in firing order:\
\
\'95  REGIME \'97 stage, SPY/200dma, IVR, VIX, gate states.\
\'95  APPROACHING THRESHOLDS \'97 informational on near-trigger signals.\
\'95  OPEN TRADES \'97 big moves, FRESH strike breaches, deeper-into-breach moves.\
\'95  ASSIGNMENT ZONE WARNING \'97 open verticals where spot is between strikes AND DTE \uc0\u8804 5. Per project_assignment_zone_friction.md: the zone where one leg gets assigned (100 shares at the short strike) and the other expires worthless. The held-to-expiry backtest engine assumes cash-equivalent settlement and does not model this friction; the alert provides the early warning so the trade can be closed intraday.\
\'95  ENTRY WINDOW APPROACHING \'97 fires from D-3 through entry day for every Window A / Window B / earnings T-1/T-3 entry. Groups by (window, opex, target).\
\'95  EX-DIV ASSIGNMENT RISK \'97 fires when an open covered_call position has ex-div within 3 trading days AND the short call is ITM or within 1% of strike. Surfaces the only mid-cycle decision point on the covered call strategy: close the call before ex-div to keep the dividend, or accept early-exercise. Filtered to structure='covered_call' (verticals have no stock leg to call away).\
\'95  EARNINGS RISK \'97 lists open positions where earnings are inside the holding window.\
\'95  52-WEEK EXTREME CONTEXT \'97 tags any open position whose underlying is within 5% of its trailing-252-day high or low. Regime context, not actionable as a filter (the 52w-extreme signal was tested as a selection filter and rejected per project_52w_extremes_rejected.md).\
\'95  IF COHORT AT 52W LOWS \'97 lists IF cohort names currently at 52w lows. Long-vol setup confirmation; informational only.\
\'95  DTE CHECKPOINTS \'97 profit-target hits, T-X warning windows, OpEx-week consolidation.\
\
When all sections are empty, the alert prints "All quiet \'97 no alerts."\
\
\b Trade construction (deployed 2026-05-01, expanded 2026-05-02)\b0\
\
scripts/monitor/trade_construction.py builds executable trade tickets for actionable rows in the daily alert, covering the four deployable structures (zebra, zebra_protected, inverted_fly, bull_put, bear_call). For every actionable row at days_until\uc0\u8804 1 the alert appends a construction block showing strikes, deltas, mids, and credit/debit, ready for the user to enter on the broker.\
\
The construction module routes by structure name to the corresponding open_* helper in scripts/backtest/structures.py \'97 the same leg-selection logic that powers the backtest. structures.py works on both ORATS by_ticker rows (backtest) and live Schwab chains (alert) because both sources expose the same column convention (strike, delta, cMidIv, pMidIv, cBidPx, cAskPx, stkPx). One source of truth for leg selection: backtest validates a method, the live system reuses the exact same code path to construct the trade. Live chain pull: lib/schwab_options.py:fetch_chain_with_greeks() with \'b13-day expiration tolerance for Schwab's Thursday vs Friday OpEx variance.\
\
Per-ticker recommendations are applied automatically before each open_* call: bull_put / bear_call rows override scripts/backtest/config.py:VERTICAL_SHORT_DELTA via moneyness_lookup.recommended_short_delta(); inverted_fly rows override BFLY_WING_PCT_SPOT via recommended_if_wing(). Each construction block annotates the per-ticker pick (or default) with the train/val p-values that earned the promotion. ZEBRA and ZEBRA-protected use their own selection logic (the practitioner search at \uc0\u8916 0.55-0.90) and are not affected by the moneyness lookup.\
\
The alert renders construction blocks in both plain-text and HTML formats. SMTP delivery via lib/email_alert.py; emails fire only when actionable rows or events are present (skip when truly quiet). Construction selection prices off the chain mid, matching the backtest's slip=0.50 assumption.\
\
\b Pricing mode (assumption to flag at execution)\b0\
\
Construction-time selection prices off the chain mid for delta-target leg picks, matching the backtest's slip=0.50 assumption. Live broker execution will see the actual bid/ask spread, not the mid \'97 a leg picked at mid may fill worse if the spread is wide on entry day. The alert emits a target credit/debit at mid; the user evaluates the live spread at entry and accepts only if the realized fill is within the slip envelope the backtest validated. Per feedback_backtest_slip_assumption_validation.md, slip assumptions are the binding test: a structure validated at slip=0.50 must also fill at slip=0.50 in live execution before live capital is committed. The covered-call demotion (v2.1) is the cautionary precedent.\
\
\b Daily ORATS forward-collection pipeline (deployed 2026-05-02)\b0\
\
scripts/orats/* runs at 7 PM ET each weekday and refreshes the by_ticker ORATS parquets used by the backtest engine and by every walk-forward refresh. The pipeline is idempotent (re-running a date does not corrupt prior data) and supports backfill ranges. An 11-day backfill (2026-04-22 to 2026-05-01) was executed as the bring-up validation. SFTP credentials are in scripts/orats/config.py (gitignored per feedback_orats_config_gitignore.md). Cleanup runs after each tier per project_orats_cleanup_plan.md.\
\
The recommendation parquets (bull_put / bear_call moneyness, IF wing width, ZEBRA cohort) are not regenerated daily \'97 they are refreshed quarterly or on cohort change by re-running the corresponding *_walkforward.py and *_followup.py scripts in scripts/backtest/. The daily ORATS refresh keeps the by_ticker parquets current so those refreshes always run on up-to-date history when triggered.\

\f0\b\fs28 What Doesn\'92t Work (Caveats for bull_put and bear_call)\

\f1\b0\fs24 Each item below has been tested and found null or negative. This section exists so future iterations of the plan do not re-derive empirically falsified ideas.\
\
\b MP anchoring for bear_call\b0\
\
\'95  MP-anchored bear_call at T-5 held to expiry does NOT lift over 30-delta (Phase 2c). MP-anchoring helps puts, not calls. The asymmetry is load-bearing.\
\'95  Aggressive ITM MP-anchored bear_call (spot > MP entry) fails standalone across 2,686 cycles. Cohort mean -$0.087 per cycle, 21.7% win rate. Regime-contingent only.\
\
\b Entry filters\b0\
\
\'95  Live-book signature (IV rank >= 0.7 + VRP > 0 + ITM short delta) does NOT lift Phase 2h baseline. Tighter thresholds make results worse.\
\'95  Mean-reverter cohort (CNC, TJX, NEE, T, GILD, PFE, MSFT, VZ, RIO) does NOT transfer to bear_call edge on 5-day OpEx trades. Mean-reverter cohort is actually worse than pinner cohort.\
\'95  Overbought signals (SPY > +10% over 200dma) are DIS-informative \'97 9.7% crash rate, 0.63x lift. Strong bull runs statistically predict continued calm.\
\'95  Single-feature quintile cuts on entry features (cushion, credit, IV) are non-monotonic. No feature ordering predicts cycle outcome.\
\
\b Stops and management\b0\
\
\'95  T-3 exit rule hurts 7 of 8 premium-seller structures. Theta harvest lives in the final 2 days.\
\'95  MTM-based mid-cycle stop (close if MTM <= 0 on Tuesday) \'97 76.8% of red-Tuesday cycles recover by expiry.\
\'95  Spot-based stops on short puts crystallize losses that would have reverted. Short puts mean-revert intraweek at OpEx.\
\'95  Signal filter (contango + VRP > 0) applied at a roll trigger day destroys edge. It is an entry filter, not a roll filter.\
\
\b Timing and regime signals\b0\
\
\'95  Daily IV-HV crossovers are too noisy for standalone use.\
\'95  Weekly IV-HV crossovers provide only modest lift (<=1.1x bull persistence) and miss Dec 2018 and Volmageddon entirely.\
\'95  No single signal (or tested composite) reliably predicts all tested downturns. Two of five came from stable positive VRP with no advance warning.\
\'95  "Boom from tranquility" events are irreducible surprises. Defined-risk structure is the only defense.\
\
\b Trend-change signals (tested 2026-04-24)\b0\
\
\'95  \b Elevated 25-delta put-call skew is DIS-informative as a sell signal on SPY.\b0  Elevated skew (top 20% of 252-day rank) precedes fwd 25-day return of +2.62% vs +1.19% baseline. Fear-is-bullish: when everyone is paying up for puts they are already hedged, and the market tends to mean-revert upward from those moments. Do not add skew to downsize triggers.\
\'95  \b RSI-14 bearish divergence (SPY at 20d high, RSI not) is DIS-informative as a sell signal.\b0  Probability of forward 25-day drawdown > -5% is 12.2% after bearish divergence vs 17.4% baseline \'97 the "trend exhaustion" interpretation fails on SPY. Do not add it to downsize triggers.\
\'95  \b RSI-14 bullish divergence (SPY at 20d low, RSI not) DOES work.\b0  Forward 25-day return +4.71% vs +1.24% baseline (~4x lift). Asymmetric: RSI divergence as a BUY signal from oversold conditions is real; as a SELL signal from overbought conditions, it is not. Candidate bull_put entry confirmation pending further testing.\
\'95  \b Mag 4 (AAPL/MSFT/META/TSLA) equal-weight vs SPY divergence:\b0  modest negative effect (fwd 25d ret +0.79% vs +1.41% baseline, N=109) but thin sample and short window (only 4.5 years of co-listed data). Not conclusive; full Mag 7 test deferred until AMZN/GOOGL/NVDA ORATS data is ingested.\
\'95  \b "Tired bull" or "overbought market" is a narrative claim, not a measurable one.\b0  No signal in our test set can quantify regime runway. Do not size down based on subjective overbought reads.\
\
\b Pin-mechanic claims\b0\
\
\'95  Max pain is not a causal attractor at T-5 entry. Price does not move toward MP more than secular drift predicts.\
\'95  Pin-break detection framework is premise-weakened for monthly OpEx. May still apply to intraday expiration dynamics but not to 5-day directional bets.\
\
\b Inverted fly management variants (tested 2026-04-24)\b0\
\
\'95  \b 21-DTE time stop (first-trigger managed exit) on inverted_fly DESTROYS the edge.\b0  Universe-wide 50%-only exit is +$0.191/cycle; first-trigger (50% or 21-DTE, whichever fires first) drops to \'96$0.004. Long-vol payoffs concentrate in the final two weeks; a time stop cuts before payoff. 50%-only is the canonical exit.\
\'95  \b Rolling at dte_21 loss check-point for inverted_fly does NOT recover edge.\b0  Tested via a proxy: if P&L at dte_21 >= 50% of debit lost, close and re-open on next monthly OpEx. Full cohort combined lift: +$0.005/cycle (noise). Tighter thresholds (75%, 100% debit lost) give negative lift. Rolling after a mid-cycle loss does not pay.\
\'95  \b Stop-loss at dte_21 loss check-point HURTS inverted_fly.\b0  Full cohort lift \'96$0.005/cycle at 50%-debit threshold; near-zero at tighter thresholds. Cutting losers also crystallizes temporary losses that would have reverted by expiration. Same mechanism as the Phase 2f bull_put spot-stop finding. Caveat: this tests one mid-cycle check-point, not a true daily-marks stop. A daily-marks stop remains untested but unlikely to rescue given the directional finding.\
\'95  \b Near-OpEx (T-5) entry for inverted_fly FAILS.\b0  Mean +$0.041/cycle vs 45-DTE +$0.191; 5\'d7 weaker. Additionally the term-inversion gate that LIFTS 45-DTE entry actively HURTS at T-5 (\'96$0.190/cycle). Same signal, opposite effect based on time-to-expiration. Do not use T-5 entry for IF.\
\

