\f0\b\fs28 Glossary\

\f1\b0\fs24 Reference for acronyms, jargon, statistical tests, and project-specific terms used throughout this plan. Organized into five alphabetized buckets. When a term or test name is unfamiliar in any section above, check here first.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Market and Options Terminology\

\f1\b0\fs24 \'95  \b ATM (at-the-money) \'97\b0  option whose strike equals (or sits closest to) current underlying spot. ATM options have the highest gamma and roughly 0.5 delta.\
\'95  \b Bid-ask spread \'97\b0  difference between the best buy price and the best sell price for an option. Wider spreads mean more slippage on entry and exit.\
\'95  \b Contango (term structure) \'97\b0  front-month implied volatility below back-month IV; the normal resting state of the IV term structure.\
\'95  \b Credit (credit spread) \'97\b0  position opened for net money received. Bull_put and bear_call verticals are credit spreads.\
\'95  \b Delta \'97\b0  sensitivity of option price to a $1 move in the underlying. Used as a rough probability of finishing in-the-money (0.30 delta short put \uc0\u8776  30% chance ITM at expiry).\
\'95  \b DTE (days to expiration) \'97\b0  days remaining until the option expires.\
\'95  \b Gamma \'97\b0  sensitivity of delta to underlying price. Highest near ATM and near expiration; drives the "short-gamma regime" risk.\
\'95  \b Implied volatility (IV) \'97\b0  forward-looking volatility priced into the option premium.\
\'95  \b In-the-money (ITM) \'97\b0  option with intrinsic value; strike is unfavorable for the seller.\
\'95  \b Inverted term structure \'97\b0  front-month IV above back-month IV. Signals expected forward vol stress.\
\'95  \b IV crush \'97\b0  rapid collapse of implied volatility, typically after a scheduled event such as earnings.\
\'95  \b Mark-to-market (MTM) \'97\b0  live P&L of an open position at current mid prices.\
\'95  \b Max loss \'97\b0  pre-defined worst-case dollar loss on a defined-risk spread (wing width \'d7 100 \'96 entry credit, for equity options).\
\'95  \b Mid pricing \'97\b0  entry or exit pricing assumed at the bid-ask midpoint. Realistic retail fills usually sit worse than mid \'97 see slip=0.25.\
\'95  \b OpEx (options expiration) \'97\b0  the monthly third-Friday expiration date. Window B trades are anchored to OpEx.\
\'95  \b Open interest (OI) \'97\b0  number of outstanding contracts at a strike. High OI is necessary for tight bid-ask and meaningful max-pain computation.\
\'95  \b Out-of-the-money (OTM) \'97\b0  option with no intrinsic value; strike is favorable for the seller.\
\'95  \b Premium \'97\b0  price of the option. For credit spreads, the credit received at entry.\
\'95  \b Realized volatility (RV) \'97\b0  historical volatility from close-to-close returns, annualized. RV20 uses a 20-trading-day window.\
\'95  \b Short gamma / short-gamma regime \'97\b0  condition where a short-option position loses money rapidly on large moves, worst in the final 1\'962 trading days before expiry.\
\'95  \b Skew (25\uc0\u916  put-call skew) \'97\b0  difference between OTM put IV and OTM call IV. Elevated skew signals expensive downside hedging.\
\'95  \b Slippage \'97\b0  execution cost away from mid. This plan uses slip=0.25 as the binding retail-friction assumption in backtests.\
\'95  \b Spot \'97\b0  current price of the underlying.\
\'95  \b Strike (K) \'97\b0  the option contract's fixed reference price.\
\'95  \b T-5 / T-1 / D-8 / D-3 \'97\b0  trading-day offsets from OpEx Friday. T-5 = 5 trading days before OpEx (prior-week Friday). D-3 = 3 trading days before (Tuesday of OpEx week).\
\'95  \b Tail risk \'97\b0  probability-weighted magnitude of worst-case losses. Defined-risk structures cap tail at max loss; undefined-risk structures (short strangle, naked short) do not.\
\'95  \b Theta \'97\b0  option's sensitivity to time passing, expressed as dollars lost per day.\
\'95  \b Theta harvest \'97\b0  premium-selling strategy profiting from daily loss of option extrinsic value.\
\'95  \b VIX \'97\b0  CBOE implied volatility index; widely-watched measure of SPX 30-day forward implied volatility.\
\'95  \b Wing (wing width) \'97\b0  dollar distance between the short strike and the long strike of a vertical, or between the short strike and either long wing of a condor or fly.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Signals and Metrics\

\f1\b0\fs24 \'95  \b 200-day moving average (200dma) \'97\b0  simple moving average of SPY daily close over 200 trading days. Used as a regime marker.\
\'95  \b 50-day moving average (50dma) \'97\b0  simple moving average of SPY daily close over 50 trading days. Used for weekly trend-persistence testing.\
\'95  \b Archetype cluster \'97\b0  k-means cluster assignment from the 2026-04-23 clustering run on 3,992 history-eligible tickers using 11 behavioral features. Cluster labels 0, 1, 2, 4 appear in this plan's universe.\
\'95  \b Extension above MP \'97\b0  (spot \'96 MP) / MP. Positive = spot above max pain; negative = below. An entry feature in Phase 2h aggressive bear_call_mp.\
\'95  \b IV rank, 252-day \'97\b0  (current ATM IV30 \'96 252d min) / (252d max \'96 252d min). Range [0, 1]. Thresholds 0.5, 0.7, and 0.9 appear in different gates.\
\'95  \b Max pain (MP) \'97\b0  argmin over strikes K of \uc0\u8721  cOI(Ks) \'d7 max(0, K \'96 Ks) + pOI(Ks) \'d7 max(0, Ks \'96 K). Computed at T-1 for the pin-reliability scan and at T-5 for entry decisions.\
\'95  \b Pinner cohort tier \'97\b0  four-tier classification of the universe by historical pin reliability: Tier 1 (credit ETFs, tightest), Tier 2 (major equity indices), Tier 3 (sector ETFs + dividend stalwarts), Tier 4 (excluded).\
\'95  \b Term spread \'97\b0  front 30-DTE ATM IV minus back 75-DTE ATM IV on SPY. Negative = contango; positive = inverted.\
\'95  \b Variance ratio (VR) \'97\b0  ratio of long-horizon variance to short-horizon variance. VR > 1 suggests trending; VR < 1 suggests mean-reverting.\
\'95  \b VRP (volatility risk premium) \'97\b0  ATM IV30 \'96 RV20. Positive = implied prices a cushion over realized; negative = realized exceeds implied.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Statistical Tests and Filters\

\f1\b0\fs24 \'95  \b Contango + VRP>0 filter (bull_put entry gate) \'97\b0  Phase 2f pre-registered entry filter. Fires when SPY term spread < 0 AND SPY VRP > 0. Tests whether these joint calm-regime conditions at T-5 entry improve bull_put_mp outcomes. Result: lifts mean from \'96$0.002 to +$0.019/cycle; fires on ~57% of historical T-5 entry days. Symmetric counterpart: when applied to inverted_fly at 45-DTE, this filter ACTIVELY HURTS (lift \'96$0.086/cycle) \'97 the two structures are entry-gate opposites.\
\'95  \b Term-inversion entry filter (inverted_fly gate) \'97\b0  Phase A IF batch (2026-04-24). Fires when SPY term_spread > 0 (front IV above back IV) at entry. Tests whether pending-vol-event signal lifts long-vol inverted_fly at 45-DTE. Result: lifts universe-wide mean from +$0.191 to +$0.639/cycle, 60.2% win to 66.6% win, N=3,303. Stacking with IVR > 0.5 lifts to +$0.697; stacking with VRP < 0 lifts to +$0.656. VALIDATED. Crucially, the same gate at T-5 near-OpEx entry ACTIVELY HURTS (mean \'96$0.190) \'97 signal has opposite effect based on time-to-expiration.\
\'95  \b Inverted_fly exit-rule comparison \'97\b0  Phase A IF batch. Tests 50%-only vs managed (first-trigger 50%/21-DTE) vs 21-DTE only exit for long-vol inverted_fly. Result: 50%-only +$0.191/cycle vs managed \'96$0.004/cycle vs 21-DTE only \'96$0.024/cycle. The 21-DTE time stop DESTROYS long-vol edge. 50%-only is the validated exit.\
\'95  \b Inverted_fly near-OpEx entry test \'97\b0  Phase B IF batch. Tests T-5 near-OpEx entry against the validated 45-DTE entry. Result: mean +$0.041/cycle (5x weaker), negative median, term-inversion gate flips destructive. FALSIFIED. Only 45-DTE entry is validated for inverted_fly.\
\'95  \b Bull_put + inverted_fly pair book \'97\b0  Phase B IF batch. Tests combined P&L of bull_put (dte_45 managed) + inverted_fly (dte_45, 10% wings, 50%-only exit) on the same (ticker, expiration, entry_date). Result: cluster-2 combined +$0.530/cycle, 56.3% win, median +$0.298, N=5,894. 39 of 57 cluster-2 names positive. Validated two-leg pair structure; SPX is the dollar anchor.\
\'95  \b H1 bear_call entry filter \'97\b0  pre-registered entry gate tested 2026-04-24. Fires when SPY < 200dma AND SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5. Tests whether regime-confirmed bear conditions rescue aggressive bear_call_mp from its \'96$0.087 baseline. Result: +$0.092/cycle, 40% win, N=102. VALIDATED \'97 the only bear_call entry gate used in this plan.\
\'95  \b H3 bear_call rolling test \'97\b0  symmetric counterpart of Phase 2g, tested 2026-04-24. Tests whether up-and-out rolling of triggered bear_call cycles into the next monthly OpEx improves outcomes. Result: FALSIFIED \'97 rolling compounds losses; only 29.6% of rolls improved the outcome.\
\'95  \b Hard pause trigger (bull_put) \'97\b0  three-condition gate that halts new bull_put entries entirely: SPY below 200dma AND term inverted AND SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.5.\
\'95  \b Live-book signature test \'97\b0  post-hoc test (2026-04-24) of the current live book's observed entry signature (IV rank \uc0\u8805  0.7 + VRP > 0 + ITM short delta) against the 2,686-cycle Phase 2h backtest. Result: NULL. The signature does not lift baseline; observed mid-cycle profit is theta noise at DTE=22.\
\'95  \b Managed exit (first-trigger 50% / 21-DTE) \'97\b0  TastyTrade-style exit rule: close at the first of (50% of max profit reached) or (DTE \uc0\u8804  21). Applied to Window A bull_put and bear_call.\
\'95  \b Mean-reverter cohort filter \'97\b0  Phase 2h sub-test. Applies bear_call_mp only to a 13-name mean-reverter cohort. Result: FAILED \'97 mean-reverters are worse than pinners for this structure.\
\'95  \b MTM-1x roll trigger (T2) \'97\b0  Phase 2g roll trigger: fire when mark-to-market loss \uc0\u8805  1\'d7 entry credit. Fires on 34.3% of bull_put_mp cycles. Dominates the spot-breach trigger (T1).\
\'95  \b Phase 1: pin reliability scan \'97\b0  19,400-cycle 13-year scan measuring median |close \'96 MP| / close and fraction of cycles within 1% of MP per ticker. Produces the four-tier pinner cohort.\
\'95  \b Phase 2c: MP-anchored structures, T-5 entry, held to expiry \'97\b0  tests whether short-strike placement nearest max pain at T-5 outperforms 30-delta for each structure. Result: bull_put_mp +$0.072/cycle, 87% win (first positive MP-flavored finding); bear_call shows no lift \'97 load-bearing asymmetry.\
\'95  \b Phase 2f: bull_put_mp rescue \'97\b0  three rescue interventions tested on bull_put_mp. Only signal-driven entry (contango + VRP>0) works; entry-feature filters and spot-based stops fail.\
\'95  \b Phase 2g: roll-to-save bull_put_mp \'97\b0  tests three triggers \'d7 two roll styles \'d7 signal gate on/off. Winning combination: T2_mtm trigger \'d7 down-and-out roll. Flips cohort mean from \'96$0.002 to +$0.014/cycle. Signal gate at trigger day HURTS.\
\'95  \b Phase 2h: aggressive ITM bear_call_mp \'97\b0  tests bear_call with spot above MP at entry and short call at the MP strike (ITM). Across 2,686 cycles: mean \'96$0.087/cycle, 21.7% win rate. FAILED standalone; regime-contingent only.\
\'95  \b Phase 2i: regime detector (planned, not run) \'97\b0  proposed multi-factor gate (VIX level, breadth, credit spreads, yield curve) for refining bear_call sizing beyond H1. Low priority given H1 is validated.\
\'95  \b Regime window tests \'97\b0  side-by-side bull_put vs bear_call tests in five backtested bear windows: COVID 2020, 2022 bear, December 2018, August 2015, Volmageddon 2018. Confirm clean sign-flipping symmetry.\
\'95  \b RSI-14 bearish divergence test \'97\b0  pre-registered test of SPY at 20-day high while RSI-14 is NOT at 20-day high. Result: DIS-informative as a sell signal (12.2% forward drawdown probability vs 17.4% baseline).\
\'95  \b RSI-14 bullish divergence test \'97\b0  tests SPY at 20-day low while RSI-14 is NOT at 20-day low. Result: +4.71% forward 25-day return vs +1.24% baseline (~4\'d7 lift). Candidate bull_put entry confirmation; not yet promoted.\
\'95  \b Skew-as-sell-signal test \'97\b0  tests whether elevated 25\uc0\u916  put-call skew (top 20% of 252-day rank) precedes negative forward returns. Result: DIS-informative. Elevated skew precedes +2.62% 25-day return vs +1.19% baseline \'97 fear-is-bullish.\
\'95  \b Soft-downsize triggers (bull_put) \'97\b0  three individual conditions, any of which halves new bull_put entry size: SPY 252-day IV rank > 0.7, SPY within 2% of 200dma from above trending down, term inverted AND VIX > 20.\
\'95  \b Spot-based stop test \'97\b0  Phase 2f sub-test. Close bull_put_mp if spot closes at or below the short strike intraweek. Result: HURTS (\'96$0.019 vs \'96$0.002 baseline). Short puts mean-revert enough that intraweek breach is not a reliable kill signal.\
\'95  \b T-3 exit rule test \'97\b0  tests whether exiting premium-seller structures 3 trading days before OpEx improves P&L. Result: HURTS 7 of 8 structures. Theta harvest lives in the final 2 trading days.\
\'95  \b T1 (Earnings \'97 bull put on bias-up) \'97\b0  pre-registered 2026-04-25; tested same day. Open a defined-risk bull put credit spread at T-3 close on names with \uc0\u8805 60% historical positive earnings rate, held to next monthly OpEx expiration. Validated at slip=0.50 with mean +$0.245/cycle, 82% win, lift +$0.289 over non-earnings control, p=0.005, N=175. Promoted to active book.\
\'95  \b T2 (Earnings \'97 bear call on bias-down) \'97\b0  symmetric counterpart of T1 on names with \uc0\u8804 40% historical positive earnings rate. Lift over control is real (+$0.188, p=0.016) but absolute mean \uc0\u8776  $0 at slip=0.50. Not promoted at cohort level. INTC carved out as a single-name positive.\
\'95  \b T3 (Earnings non-earnings control) \'97\b0  comparison cohort for T1, T2, T4. For each cohort ticker, sample 5\'d7 as many random non-earnings trading days in the same date range, \'b110-trading-day buffer around real earnings events, and run identical entry/exit logic. The lift = earnings_mean \'96 control_mean.\
\'95  \b T4 (Earnings \'97 inverted fly on high-vol bias-ambiguous) \'97\b0  long-vol structure on names with high std but no strong directional bias. Cohort inconclusive at slip=0.50 (p=0.53). PLTR single-name validated standalone: +$0.82 mean, 82% win, +$0.83 lift, T-3 entry, held to monthly OpEx.\
\'95  \b ZEBRA backtest \'97\b0  pre-registered 2026-04-25 (docs/ZEBRA_PREREG.md). 4,064 cycles at slip=0.50 across the 36-name v1.5 cohort, 75-DTE entry held to expiration. All four pre-reg hypotheses pass: extrinsic-rule fire rate ~95% (H1), flat-day MTM mean +$0.58/day with no theta drag (H2), median upside capture 1.152 (H3 \'97 ZEBRA actually beats long stock by 15% on upside cycles), capital efficiency 0.21 (H4 \'97 debit is 21% of stock cost). Walk-forward validates on 13 of 13 top names. Promoted into the plan at v1.6.\
\'95  \b Jade Lizard backtest (NOT PROMOTED) \'97\b0  pre-registered 2026-04-25. 5,110 matched cycles vs BP+BC baseline. Backtest passes 5 of 6 gates (managed-exit lift +$0.53/cycle vs baseline, p=0.002, walk-forward validates on 8 of 9 top names) but fails the defined-risk policy gate due to the naked short put leg. Stop-loss test (2026-04-25 addendum) confirms stops do not save the strategy: gap risk on bloodbath cycles eats most of the savings, and false triggers destroy wins on cycles that would have recovered. Verdict: NOT promoted; trading plan stays at v1.5 for credit-spread book. Detail: project_jade_lizard_findings.md.\
\'95  \b Term-inversion-as-bear_call-entry test \'97\b0  sub-test under H1. Tests whether adding "term inverted" to SPY<200dma + IVR>0.5 improves bear_call. Result: DIS-informative. Adding term inversion drops mean to \'96$0.152/cycle.\
\'95  \b VRP + term-structure magnitude signal \'97\b0  tests whether joint low-VRP + inverted-term-structure days predict elevated 45-day realized-move probability. Result: 4\'d7 lift on P(|return| \uc0\u8805  10%) over 45 days. Used for long-vol structure timing, not short-premium entry.\
\'95  \b Weekly IV-HV + trend persistence test \'97\b0  tests whether weekly-aggregated VRP stability plus SPY regime (> or < 50dma) predicts 5-week forward trend persistence. Result: asymmetric \'97 bull trends persist 75% of windows, bear trends only 35%. Informs bear_call deployment discipline.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Structures\

\f1\b0\fs24 \'95  \b Bear call vertical \'97\b0  short call at a lower strike + long call at a higher strike, same expiration. Credit received. Profits if the underlying stays below the short strike.\
\'95  \b Bull put vertical \'97\b0  short put at a higher strike + long put at a lower strike, same expiration. Credit received. Profits if the underlying stays above the short strike.\
\'95  \b Covered call \'97\b0  long 100 shares of underlying + short 1 call. Generates income from the call premium at the cost of capping upside. Relevant to the queued earnings-plays track.\
\'95  \b Inverted fly \'97\b0  four-leg defined-risk long-volatility structure: long 1 ATM call + long 1 ATM put (straddle body) + short 1 OTM call + short 1 OTM put (short wings). Net debit at entry. Profits on large underlying moves in either direction past the short strikes; max loss = entry debit (realized if underlying pins at ATM). Canonical wing width in this plan: 10% of spot on each side. Opposite regime from the short-premium structures \'97 pays when vol expands.\
\'95  \b Iron condor \'97\b0  bull put vertical + bear call vertical on the same expiration and underlying. Profits if underlying finishes between the two short strikes.\
\'95  \b Iron fly (iron butterfly) \'97\b0  iron condor with the two short strikes equal (typically ATM). Higher credit, narrower profit zone.\
\'95  \b Short strangle \'97\b0  short put at a lower strike + short call at a higher strike, same expiration. Undefined-risk structure; premium collected on both wings.\
\'95  \b Straddle \'97\b0  long put + long call at the same strike (typically ATM). A long-vol structure profiting on magnitude.\
\'95  \b Vertical \'97\b0  generic term for a spread combining one short leg and one long leg of the same type (both calls or both puts) on the same expiration.\
\'95  \b ZEBRA (Zero Extrinsic Back Ratio) \'97\b0  3-contract single-underlying structure: buy 2\'d7 ITM call at ~70\uc0\u916  + sell 1\'d7 ATM call at ~50\uc0\u916 . Same expiration. Net debit at entry; max loss = the debit (defined risk). Long-stock-equivalent payoff at expiry with slight delta leverage (entry net delta ~+0.90 to +1.15) and positive gamma. Designed to replicate stock exposure without time decay: when extrinsic_short \uc0\u8805  2\'d7 extrinsic_long_total at entry, net theta is zero or positive.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 Project and Research Terms\

\f1\b0\fs24 \'95  \b AUDIT.md \'97\b0  five-tier feature scorecard at ~/Metal_Project/AUDIT.md. Governs what migrates from Metal_Project into MaxPain_Project.\
\'95  \b Backtest v1 / v2 \'97\b0  Track A backtest engine versions. v1 used fixed $1 wings (too narrow for SPY-type names); v2 scaled wings to 0.25%/0.5% of spot with mid pricing.\
\'95  \b bull_put_mp / bear_call_mp \'97\b0  MP-anchored variants of the vertical structures: short strike placed nearest max pain at T-5 entry.\
\'95  \b Down-and-out roll \'97\b0  roll style that reopens at the new MP strike on the new chain. Beats straight-out in Phase 2g bull_put rolling.\
\'95  \b MaxPain_Project \'97\b0  new project home at ~/MaxPain_Project/ (scaffold created 2026-04-17). Migration target for the trading system.\
\'95  \b Metal_Project \'97\b0  original project home at ~/Metal_Project/. Live DB and existing Streamlit dashboards remain there during the audit and bake-off.\
\'95  \b ORATS \'97\b0  options historical data vendor. Provides the 13-year chain history used for backtests.\
\'95  \b Paper-test window \'97\b0  paper-only discipline period through approximately 2026-08-19. No live capital committed before that date regardless of results.\
\'95  \b slip=0.25 \'97\b0  backtest friction assumption: \'bc of the bid-ask half-spread of slippage on each leg. Represents realistic retail fill quality \'97 edge that disappears at slip=0.25 is not edge.\
\'95  \b Straight-out roll \'97\b0  roll style that keeps the original short strike on the new expiration. Inferior to down-and-out for bull_put rolling.\
\'95  \b Synthetic non-earnings control \'97\b0  per-ticker random sample of trading days in the same date range as the real earnings events, with a \'b110-trading-day buffer to ensure no overlap. Used to compute the lift_vs_control statistic for any earnings-aligned trade rule. Sample ratio: 5\'d7 the real-event count per ticker. Defined and first used in the T3 pre-registration.\
\'95  \b Track A / Track B \'97\b0  backtest scope. Track A covers OpEx-window premium-seller structures on the 150-universe; Track B reserved for earnings plays (pending data).\
\'95  \b Universe v1 \'97\b0  frozen 150-symbol list at ~/MaxPain_Project/data/profile/universe_v1.parquet, dated 2026-04-23. Does not change during the paper-test window.\
\'95  \b Window A \'97\b0  45-DTE managed entry window. Managed exit: first trigger of 50% max profit or DTE \uc0\u8804  21.\
\'95  \b Window B \'97\b0  near-OpEx theta harvest window. Enter T-5; exit per structure (bull_put_mp held to expiration).\
\

\f0\b\fs28 Regime Health Monitor\

\f1\b0\fs24 \i Scope: continuous post-entry surveillance of the same signals that gate entry. The qualifier evaluates gates once per cycle to decide GO/SKIP; the regime-health monitor evaluates them every day to flag when a previously-satisfied gate is degrading. Built 2026-05-03. Independent module at scripts/monitor/regime_health.py.\i0\
\
The entry gates are point-in-time checks. They tell us a trade should be opened today; they say nothing about whether yesterday's trade is still in a supportive regime today. Without continuous surveillance, the only signal that an open position has drifted into adverse conditions is the realized P&L on the exit \'97 too late to prevent. The Regime Health Monitor closes that loop: same signals, evaluated daily, rendered as 🟢 / 🟡 / 🔴 indicators in the 4:45 PM email, persisted to history for retrospective audit.\
\
\b Three layers\b0\
\
\'95  \b System level \'97 per structure family.\b0  Each entry-gate component reads as 🟢 (healthy, outside the warning band of its threshold), 🟡 (within the warning band but not yet violated), or 🔴 (violated). Composite status per family aggregates: 0\'d70 \uc0\u8594  HEALTHY, any \u8804 1 \u8594  DEGRADING, any \u8805 1 violated \u8594  GATE INACTIVE. The 5-day delta is shown inline as a velocity readout \'97 a healthy component with a sharp adverse delta is tomorrow's warning.\
\'95  \b Per-position level.\b0  For every open placed=1 position, render a line showing the underlying's spot vs its 200-DMA, directionally adjusted (bullish bias for bull_put / zebra / stock / covered_call; bearish bias for bear_call). Combined status is the worst-of(system_status, name_status) for that position.\
\'95  \b Persistence layer.\b0  Three new SQLite tables capture the snapshot daily: regime_health_snapshots (one row per (date, family, component)), regime_health_composites (one row per (date, family) with composite verdict), position_health_snapshots (one row per (date, trade_id) with combined status). After 30-60 days the audit query becomes meaningful: "How many days before bull_put_signal_active actually flipped did the warning band fire?" "When position health turned 🟡 mid-trade, what was the median P&L change over the next N days?" Feedback loop on the early-warning system itself.\
\
\b Coverage by family\b0\
\
\'95  \b bull_put.\b0  4-component check: term_spread<0 (contango) + VRP>0 + SPY\uc0\u8805 200-DMA + IVR<0.50. The first two define bull_put_signal_active in the qualifier; the last two together reproduce the hard-pause precondition (paired with term inversion). All four watched simultaneously gives the earliest cross-component degradation signal.\
\'95  \b bear_call.\b0  2-component check: SPY<200-DMA + IVR>0.50 (the H1 gate). When H1 was active at entry but is now degrading or broken, the regime that justified the bear_call has flipped \'97 the position is in adverse conditions even though defined-risk still holds.\
\'95  \b zebra.\b0  No SPY-level system gate \'97 ZEBRA's entry-time discipline is the per-name 200-DMA persistence filter. The system block reports "N/A \'97 see per-position lines" and the per-position block carries the load. Each open ZEBRA gets a name-level 200-DMA reading.\
\'95  \b inverted_fly.\b0  Explicitly exempted. Inverted fly is directionally neutral (long-vol structure that profits on significant moves either direction); a 🟢 / 🔴 system framing doesn't fit. Continuous surveillance for IF positions is via the existing 50%-profit and DTE-band alerts, not regime monitoring.\
\
\b Warning bands (gate_config.py)\b0\
\
\'95  TERM_SPREAD_NEAR_BAND = 0.005 \'97 term_spread within 0.005 of 0 \uc0\u8594  🟡\
\'95  VRP_NEAR_BAND = 0.005 \'97 VRP within 0.005 of 0 \uc0\u8594  🟡\
\'95  SPY_MA200_NEAR_PCT = 0.03 \'97 SPY within 3% of 200-DMA in adverse direction \uc0\u8594  🟡\
\'95  IVR_NEAR_BAND = 0.10 \'97 IVR within 0.10 of 0.50 threshold \uc0\u8594  🟡\
\'95  SPOT_MA200_NEAR_PCT = 0.03 \'97 per-position: spot within 3% of 200-DMA in adverse direction \uc0\u8594  🟡\
\'95  TREND_VELOCITY_LOOKBACK_DAYS = 5 \'97 5-day Δ for velocity readout\
\
\b Strategic implication \'97 mechanical early exit enables size-up\b0\
\
The framework's value is operational discipline, but the broader thesis is that mechanical early-exit triggers reduce realized loss vs theoretical max loss. If warnings reliably fire N days before realized losses mature on a name, the effective max loss per position is "loss accumulated up to the warning" rather than "structural max loss at expiry" \'97 smaller than the dollar-risk budget assumed. This in principle allows a stepped size-up to maintain the same dollar risk per position at higher contract count.\
\
The conditional matters: this is a hypothesis, not a deployment-ready conclusion. The persistence layer is the test. After 2-3 OpEx cycles of audit data, query position_health_snapshots joined to closed spread_score_trades to compute the actual lead-time distribution and the loss-reduction-vs-held-to-expiry counterfactual. \i If\i0  that data shows reliable lead-time of \uc0\u8805 2 days for \u8805 70% of names, then a stepped size-up (1.25\'d7 \u8594  1.5\'d7 \u8594  2\'d7) becomes data-supported. If the lead-time data is inconsistent or warnings come too late on adverse names, the framework remains valuable for risk awareness but does NOT justify size-up. Through the paper-test window (2026-08-19 gate per project_paper_test_window.md), sizing remains paper-policy; the size-up question is post-gate.\
\
Caveats:\
\'95  \b Gap risk bypasses the monitor.\b0  Earnings overnight gaps, macro shocks, circuit-breaker days can produce simultaneous warning AND max-loss in the same day. The 200-DMA monitor doesn't help when SPY is down 4% pre-market. Defined-risk caps still hold (the floor is the floor); the early-exit thesis is about the slow-grind cases, not tail events.\
\'95  \b N=0 at deployment.\b0  The system fires its first email 2026-05-04. The audit substrate is the path to data; until that data accumulates, treat the warnings as risk awareness, not as size-up justification.\
\'95  \b False positives on whipsaws.\b0  A 🟡 reading that reverses to 🟢 within days is noise; the audit will reveal whether warning persistence (e.g., requiring 3 consecutive 🟡 days before alerting on a position) reduces false positives. Initial threshold is single-day; revisit after first cycle of data.\
\
Detail: project_regime_health_monitor.md.\
